Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Boil a full #kettle{}.

Peel the @garlic{2%cloves}, leaving the cloves whole.

In an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}, combine the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g} and garlic cloves. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt and @ground black pepper{}, then mix well.

Place the @Greek style salad cheese{100%g} in the centre of the mixture.

Bake on the middle shelf of your oven until the tomatoes are bursting and the cheese is turning golden, ~{25-30%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pour the water from the kettle into a large #saucepan{}. Add @salt{1/2%tsp} and bring to the boil.

When boiling, add the @rigatoni pasta{180%g} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, reserve some @reserved pasta water{100%ml}, then drain in a #colander{}. Drizzle with @oil and stir through to prevent it from sticking.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{240%g} to the pan and season with @salt and @ground black pepper{}. Fry until golden brown on the outside and cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and utensils after handling raw meat. Cook so there's no pink in the middle.

Once the cheese is golden, remove the dish from the oven and add the @sugar{1%tsp} and @butter{30%g}. Sprinkle with the @dried oregano{1%sachet} and @chilli flakes{1%pinch} (add less if you prefer things milder).

Use a #potato masher{} or #fork{} to mash the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%g}, garlic and tomatoes together into a chunky sauce.

Once the sauce has a chunky consistency, stir in the cooked chicken, pasta, reserved pasta water, @pesto{32%g} and hard Italian style cheese.

Season with @salt and @ground black pepper{}, then mix well until creamy. Add a splash of @?water{} if you feel it needs it.

Divide the cheesy baked pasta between your #bowls{}.

Top the pasta with the @wild rocket{20%g}(leaves only) and drizzle with the @oil to finish.

Enjoy!